Motivation and Goals

  • Copious amounts of transactions data are produced not just in industry, but in healthcare claims
  • The curse of dimensionality makes explaining some of the relationships between item co-occurrence difficult
  • Solution: use visualization as a decision support tool–by displaying large amounts of data in concise ways, new patterns may be revealed

What we have

Data from Medicare synthetic PUF Sample 1. You can learn more about Medicare data here

What we want

Zhou X, Menche J, Barabasi AL, Sharma A. Human symptoms-disease network. Nature communications; 26 June 2014. DOI: 10.1038/ncomms5212. http://barabasi.com/f/479.pdf

Step 1: Translate Codes

We will use the Clinical Classification Software provided by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality to translate codes

  • Produces meaningful descriptions
  • Reduces dimensionality

Patient 118 had an acute myocardial infarction (heart attack), and patient 115 has an alcohol related disorder.

We have 47659 rows representing the same number of patients, and we have 206 columns representing that many diagnoses.

Step 3: Calculate co-incidences

There's a great package called arules, we can use its depth-first algorithm to calculate some interesting measures of association. Here's what some of the metrics look like:
